# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-ink-ratio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Markings and visual elements can be called chartjunk if they are not part of the minimum set of visuals necessary to communicate the information understandably.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Another kind of chartjunk skews the depiction and makes it difficult to understand the real data being displayed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Examples of this type include items depicted out of scale to one another, noisy backgrounds making comparison between elements difficult in a chart or graph, and 3-D simulations in line and bar charts.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] The term *chartjunk* was coined by Edward Tufte in his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* based on ideas and materials developed for a Princeton statistics course co-taught with John Tukey.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] The term has been associated with Tufte in other references.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] In *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* Tufte claims that good design is founded in minimalist design principles.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Specifically, he states that "graphics reveal data" if they are designed with "graphical integrity." Tufte, through minimalist design principles, was committed to an objective and neutral values of science.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Other researchers have argued that minimalism is not objective and is full of its own rhetoric and potential to bias.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Tufte, in coining the term chartjunk, also made direct comments about a well-known designer at that time, Nigel Holmes.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] This debate between Tufte and Holmes is emblematic of the tension between statistical and designerly approaches to visualization design.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] The term chartjunk is an umbrella term that can be used to describe a variety of visual devices and has been referenced by different terms across research.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Alternative terms include *embellishment,* *excessive annotation*, decoration, *extraneous elements*, and *unnecessary ornamentation*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] Robert Kosara, also a data visualization practitioner, researcher, and author of the blog EagerEyes, noted that not all chartjunk are the same, some are harmful (e.g. a busy background), others harmless (e.g. nice borders or pictures), and some even helpful (e.g. annotations).
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] In a recent study by Parsons and Shukla, they interviewed data visualization designers and found that there is both a "corrective movement" in the design community to move away from minimalist design principles, but also, that designers had different definitions for what constitutes chartjunk.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] The information visualization research community has researched the effects of chartjunk on how viewers interpret visualizations.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] There have been studies that found that chartjunk increases long-term memorability of the chart.
[src:data-ink-ratio/chartjunk] A recent study found that chartjunk, in the form of semantically meaningful icons, increased accessibility of charts for people with Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities (IDD).
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Edward Rolf Tufte was born in 1942 in Kansas City, Missouri, to Virginia Tufte (1918–2020) and Edward E.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He grew up in Beverly Hills, California, where his father was a longtime city official.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He graduated from the public Beverly Hills High School.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte received a BS and a MS in statistics from Stanford University, and a Doctor of Philosophy in political science from Yale University.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] His dissertation was completed in 1968 and titled *The Civil Rights Movement and Its Opposition*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte was hired in 1967 by the Woodrow Wilson School of Princeton University as a lecturer in politics and public affairs, where he steadily moved up to the rank of full Professor in 1972.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He taught courses there in political economy and data analysis while publishing three quantitatively inclined political science books.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In 1975, while at Princeton, Tufte was asked to teach a statistics course to a group of journalists who were visiting the school to study economics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He developed a set of readings and lectures on statistical graphics, which he further developed in joint seminars he taught with renowned statistician John Tukey, a pioneer in the field of information design.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] These course materials became the foundation for Tufte's first book on information design, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In 1977, Tufte left Princeton University for Yale University, where he accepted an appointment as Professor of Political Science, Statistics, and Computer Science, as well as a Senior Critic at the Yale School of Art.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] After negotiations with major publishers failed, Tufte decided to self-publish the book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* in 1982, working closely with graphic designer Howard Gralla.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte financed the work by taking out a second mortgage on his home.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] The book quickly became a commercial success and secured Tufte's transition from political scientist to information expert.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In 1999, after 22 years of service at Yale University, his professorship at Yale was made Emeritus.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] On March 5, 2010, President Barack Obama appointed Tufte to the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act's Recovery Independent Advisory Panel "to provide transparency in the use of Recovery-related funds".
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte is an expert in the presentation of infographics such as charts and diagrams, and is a fellow of the American Statistical Association.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He has held fellowships from the Guggenheim Foundation and the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte's writing is important in such fields as information design and visual literacy, which deal with the visual communication of information.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He coined the word *chartjunk* to refer to useless, non-informative, or information-obscuring elements of quantitative information displays.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte's other key concepts include what he calls the *lie factor*, the *data-ink ratio*, and the *data density* of a graphic.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte uses the term "data-ink ratio" to argue against using excessive decoration in visual displays of quantitative information.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In *Visual Display*, Tufte explains, "Sometimes decoration can help editorialize about the substance of the graphic.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte encourages the use of data-rich illustrations that present all available data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] When such illustrations are examined closely, every data point has a value, but when they are looked at more generally, only trends and patterns can be observed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte suggests these macro/micro readings be presented in the space of an eye-span, in the high resolution format of the printed page, and at the unhurried pace of the viewer's leisure.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte uses several historical examples to make his case.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] These include John Snow's cholera outbreak map, Charles Joseph Minard's *Carte Figurative*, early space debris plots, Galileo Galilei's *Sidereus Nuncius*, and Maya Lin's Vietnam Veterans Memorial.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] For instance, the listing of the names of deceased soldiers on the black granite of Lin's sculptural memorial is shown to be more powerful as a chronological list rather than as an alphabetical one.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] The sacrifice each fallen individual has made is thus highlighted within the overall time scope of the war.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In *Sidereus Nuncius*, Galileo presents the nightly observations of the moons of Jupiter in relation to the body itself, interwoven with the two-month narrative record.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte has criticized the way Microsoft PowerPoint is typically used.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte cites the way PowerPoint was used by NASA engineers in the events leading to the Space Shuttle Columbia disaster as an example of PowerPoint's many problems.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] The software style is designed to persuade rather than to inform people of technical details.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Instead, Tufte argues that the most effective way of presenting information in a technical setting, such as an academic seminar or a meeting of industry experts, is by distributing a brief written report that can be read by all participants in the first 5 to 10 minutes of the meeting.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte believes that this is the most efficient method of transferring knowledge from the presenter to the audience and then the rest of the meeting is devoted to discussion and debate.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] One method Tufte encourages to allow quick visual comparison of multiple series is the small multiple, a chart with many series shown on a single pair of axes that can often be easier to read when displayed as several separate pairs of axes placed next to each other.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] He suggests this is particularly helpful when the series are measured on quite different vertical (*y*-axis) scales, but over the same range on the horizontal *x*-axis (usually time).
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] These are often used as elements of a small multiple with several lines used together.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Tufte explains the sparkline as a kind of "word" that conveys rich information without breaking the flow of a sentence or paragraph made of other "words" both visual and conventional.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] To date, the earliest known implementation of sparklines was conceived by interaction designer Peter Zelchenko and implemented by programmer Mike Medved in early 1998.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Beyond his academic endeavors over the years, Tufte has created sculptures, often large outdoor ones made of metal or stone, that were first primarily exhibited on his own rural Connecticut property.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In 2009–10, some of these artworks were exhibited at the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum in Ridgefield, Connecticut, in the one-man show *Edward Tufte: Seeing Around*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] Hogpen Hill Farms, the 234-acre (95-hectare) Tufte sculpture garden in Woodbury, Connecticut, is open to the public on summer weekends.
[src:data-ink-ratio/edward-tufte] In 2010, Edward Tufte opened a gallery, ET Modern, in New York City's Chelsea Art District at 11th Avenue and 20th Street.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:data-ink-ratio/information-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In statistics, a **misleading graph**, also known as a **distorted graph**, is a graph that misrepresents data, constituting a misuse of statistics and with the result that an incorrect conclusion may be derived from it.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs may be misleading by being excessively complex or poorly constructed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Even when constructed to display the characteristics of their data accurately, graphs can be subject to different interpretations, or unintended kinds of data can seemingly and ultimately erroneously be derived.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs may be created intentionally to hinder the proper interpretation of data or accidentally due to unfamiliarity with graphing software, misinterpretation of data, or because data cannot be accurately conveyed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs are often used in false advertising.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] One of the first authors to write about misleading graphs was Darrell Huff, publisher of the 1954 book *How to Lie with Statistics*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] He has also highlighted the concentration of data scientists in employment by technology companies, which he believes can result in the hampering of the evaluation of their visualisations due to the proprietary and closed nature of much of the data they work with.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The field of data visualization describes ways to present information that avoids creating misleading graphs.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] There are numerous ways in which a misleading graph may be constructed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The use of graphs where they are not needed can lead to unnecessary confusion/interpretation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Generally, the more explanation a graph needs, the less the graph itself is needed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs do not always convey information better than tables.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The use of biased or loaded words in the graph's title, axis labels, or caption may inappropriately prime the reader.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Similarly, attempting to draw trend lines through uncorrelated data may mislead the reader into believing a trend exists where there is none.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] This can be both the result of intentionally attempting to mislead the reader or due to the phenomenon of illusory correlation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Comparing data on barcharts is generally much easier.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In the image below, it is very hard to tell where the blue sector is bigger than the green sector on the piecharts.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A *perspective* (3D) pie chart is used to give the chart a 3D look.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Often used for aesthetic reasons, the third dimension does not improve the reading of the data; on the contrary, these plots are difficult to interpret because of the distorted effect of perspective associated with the third dimension.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The use of superfluous dimensions not used to display the data of interest is discouraged for charts in general, not only for pie charts.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In a 3D pie chart, the slices that are closer to the reader appear to be larger than those in the back due to the angle at which they're presented.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Item C appears to be at least as large as Item A in the misleading pie chart, whereas in actuality, it is less than half as large.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Item D looks a lot larger than item B, but they are the same size.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Using pictograms in bar graphs should not be scaled uniformly, as this creates a perceptually misleading comparison.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The area of the pictogram is interpreted instead of only its height or width.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] This causes the scaling to make the difference appear to be squared.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In the improperly scaled pictogram bar graph, the image for B is actually 9 times as large as A.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The perceived size increases when scaling.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The effect of improper scaling of pictograms is further exemplified when the pictogram has 3 dimensions, in which case the effect is cubed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The graph of house sales (left) is misleading.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] It appears that home sales have grown eightfold in 2001 over the previous year, whereas they have actually grown twofold.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Besides, the number of sales is not specified.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] An improperly scaled pictogram may also suggest that the item itself has changed in size.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Assuming the pictures represent equivalent quantities, the misleading graph shows that there are more bananas because the bananas occupy the most area and are furthest to the right.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Logarithmic (or log) scales are a valid means of representing data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] But when used without being clearly labeled as log scales or displayed to a reader unfamiliar with them, they can be misleading.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Log scales put the data values in terms of a chosen number (often 10) to a particular power.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] For example, log scales may give a height of 1 for a value of 10 in the data and a height of 6 for a value of 1,000,000 (106) in the data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Log scales and variants are commonly used, for instance, for the volcanic explosivity index, the Richter scale for earthquakes, the magnitude of stars, and the pH of acidic and alkaline solutions.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Even in these cases, the log scale can make the data less apparent to the eye.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Often the reason for the use of log scales is that the graph's author wishes to display vastly different scales on the same axis.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Without log scales, comparing quantities such as 1000 (103) versus 109 (1,000,000,000) becomes visually impractical.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A graph with a log scale that was not clearly labeled as such, or a graph with a log scale presented to a viewer who did not know logarithmic scales, would generally result in a representation that made data values look of similar size, in fact, being of widely differing magnitudes.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Misuse of a log scale can make vastly different values (such as 10 and 10,000) appear close together (on a base-10 log scale, they would be only 1 and 4).
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Or it can make small values appear to be negative due to how logarithmic scales represent numbers smaller than one.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Misuse of log scales may also cause relationships between quantities to appear linear whilst those relationships are exponentials or power laws that rise very rapidly towards higher values.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] It has been stated, although mainly in a humorous way, that "anything looks linear on a log-log plot with thick marker pen" .
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Both graphs show an identical exponential function of *f(x*) = 2*x*.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The graph on the left uses a linear scale, showing clearly an exponential trend.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The graph on the right, however uses a logarithmic scale, which generates a straight line.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] If the graph viewer were not aware of this, the graph would appear to show a linear trend.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A **truncated graph** (also known as a **torn graph**) has a *y* axis that does not start at 0.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] These graphs can create the impression of important change where there is relatively little change.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] While truncated graphs can be used to overdraw differences or to save space, their use is often discouraged.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Commercial software such as MS Excel will tend to truncate graphs by default if the values are all within a narrow range, as in this example.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] To show relative differences in values over time, an index chart can be used.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Truncated diagrams will always distort the underlying numbers visually.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Several studies found that even if people were correctly informed that the y-axis was truncated, they still overestimated the actual differences, often substantially.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] These graphs display *identical data*; however, in the truncated bar graph on the left, the data *appear* to show significant differences, whereas, in the regular bar graph on the right, these differences are hardly visible.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Changing the *y*-axis maximum affects how the graph appears.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A higher maximum will cause the graph to appear to have less volatility, less growth, and a less steep line than a lower maximum.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Changing the ratio of a graph's dimensions will affect how the graph appears.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The scales of a graph are often used to exaggerate or minimize differences.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The lack of a starting value for the *y* axis makes it unclear whether the graph is truncated.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Additionally, the lack of tick marks prevents the reader from determining whether the graph bars are properly scaled.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Without a scale, the visual difference between the bars can be easily manipulated.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Though all three graphs share the same data, and hence the actual slope of the (*x*, *y*) data is the same, the way that the data is plotted can change the visual appearance of the angle made by the line on the graph.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] This is because each plot has a different scale on its vertical axis.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Because the scale is not shown, these graphs can be misleading.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The intervals and units used in a graph may be manipulated to create or mitigate change expression.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs created with omitted data remove information from which to base a conclusion.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In the scatter plot with missing categories on the left, the growth appears to be more linear with less variation.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In financial reports, negative returns or data that do not correlate with a positive outlook may be excluded to create a more favorable visual impression.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The use of a superfluous third dimension, which does not contain information, is strongly discouraged, as it may confuse the reader.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs are designed to allow easier interpretation of statistical data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] However, graphs with excessive complexity can obfuscate the data and make interpretation difficult.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Poorly constructed graphs can make data difficult to discern and thus interpret.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Misleading graphs may be used in turn to extrapolate misleading trends.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Several methods have been developed to determine whether graphs are distorted and to quantify this distortion.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A graph with a high lie factor (>1) would exaggerate change in the data it represents, while one with a small lie factor (>0, <1) would obscure change in the data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] A perfectly accurate graph would exhibit a lie factor of 1.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The **graph discrepancy index**, also known as the **graph distortion index** (**GDI**), was originally proposed by Paul John Steinbart in 1998.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] GDI is calculated as a percentage ranging from −100% to positive infinity, with zero percent indicating that the graph has been properly constructed and anything outside the ±5% margin is considered to be distorted.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Research into the usage of GDI as a measure of graphics distortion has found it to be inconsistent and discontinuous, making the usage of GDI as a measurement for comparisons difficult.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The data-ink ratio should be relatively high.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Otherwise, the chart may have unnecessary graphics.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The data density should be relatively high, otherwise a table may be better suited for displaying the data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs are useful in the summary and interpretation of financial data.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs allow trends in large data sets to be seen while also allowing the data to be interpreted by non-specialists.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Graphs are often used in corporate annual reports as a form of impression management.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] In the United States, graphs do not have to be audited, as they fall under AU Section 550 Other Information in Documents Containing Audited Financial Statements.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Several published studies have looked at the usage of graphs in corporate reports for different corporations in different countries and have found frequent usage of improper design, selectivity, and measurement distortion within these reports.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The presence of misleading graphs in annual reports has led to requests for standards to be set.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Research has found that readers with poor levels of financial understanding have a greater chance of being misinformed by misleading graphs.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] Those with financial understanding, such as loan officers, may still be misled.
[src:data-ink-ratio/misleading-graph] The perception of graphs is studied in psychophysics, cognitive psychology, and computational visions.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] A **sparkline** is a very small line chart, typically drawn without axes or coordinates.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] It presents the general shape of a variation (typically over time) in some measurement, such as temperature or stock market price, in a simple and highly condensed way.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Whereas a typical chart is designed to professionally show as much data as possible, and is set off from the flow of text, sparklines are intended to be succinct, memorable, and located where they are discussed.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Sparklines are small enough to be embedded in text, or several sparklines may be grouped together as elements of a small multiple.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] In 1762 Laurence Sterne used typographical devices in his sixth volume of The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman to illustrate his narrative proceeding: "These were the four lines I moved through my first, second, third, and fourth volumes,–".
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] The 1888 monograph describing the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa shows barometric signatures of the event obtained at various stations around the world in the same fashion, but in separate plates (VII & VIII), not within the text.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Edward Tufte documented a compact style in 1983 called "intense continuous time-series".
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] He introduced the term *sparkline* in 2006 for "small, high resolution graphics embedded in a context of words, numbers, images", which are "data-intense, design-simple, word-sized graphics".
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Later in 2020, Tufte attributed the idea to Donald Knuth's "METAFONTbook".
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] The first software sparkline was programmed in 1999 by Peter Zelchenko.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] He introduced "an inline-chart" feature for Mike Medved's QuoteTracker.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] TD Ameritrade later discontinued QuoteTracker.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] On May 7, 2008, Microsoft employees filed a patent application for the implementation of sparklines in Microsoft Excel 2010.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] The application was published on November 12, 2009, prompting Tufte to express concerns about patent breadth and non-novelty.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] On 23 January, 2009, MultiRacio Ltd. published an OpenOffice.org Calc extension named "EuroOffice Sparkline".
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] On March 3, 2022, Tomaž Vajngerl implemented sparklines in LibreOffice Calc version 7.4, including support for importing sparklines from the OOXML Workbook format.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Sparklines are frequently used in line with text.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] The sparkline should be about the same height as the text around it.
[src:data-ink-ratio/sparkline] Tufte offers some useful design principles for the sizing of sparklines to maximize their readability.
